{"title_page": "Don't Touch Me", "text_new": "{{about||[[Busta Rhymes]] song|Don't Touch Me (Throw da Water on 'em)|the book|Here's the Deal: Don't Touch Me}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Touch Me\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--Don't Touch Me 1966.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| album      = [[The Seely Style]]\n| B-side     = \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|03}}\n| format     = [[gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = February 12, 1966\n| studio     = Fred Foster Sound Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=59}}\n| label      = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer     = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| producer   = [[Fred Foster]]\n| prev_title = Today Is Not the Day\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\n'''\"Don't Touch Me\"''' is a song written by [[Hank Cochran]]. It was originally written for and recorded by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. The song was released as a single on [[Monument Records]] in 1966 and became a major ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country hit. \"Don't Touch Me\" became Seely's [[signature song]] and her biggest hit as a solo artist. It would later appear on her [[The Seely Style|debut studio album]] and be re-recorded by Seely in later years. \n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" has been covered by various artists. It was also notably covered by American country artist [[Wilma Burgess]] around the same time as the original version. Burgess's version was released shortly after Seely's recording. The song became a major hit for Burgess as well, but reached a lower position on the ''Billboard'' country chart in comparison with Seely's. Burgess's cover of \"Don't Touch\" appeared on her studio album of the same name. \n\n==Background and recording==\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was originally written by songwriter [[Hank Cochran]]. Country artist [[Buck Owens]] had first wanted to record the track for himself. However, Cochran was not set on having Owens record it.<ref name=\"Country Thang\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Arden |title=A Rather \u2018Risky\u2019 Song, \u201cDon\u2019t Touch Me\u201d Became A Hit |url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/risky-dont-touch-seely/ |website=Country Thang Daily |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> At the same time, Jeannie Seely had just moved from [[California]] to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to pursue a music career. Cochran had promised Seely the opportunity to collaborate musically. When she asked Cochran if the offer still stood, Cochran replied, \"Yes, if you're going to let me make the decisions and do what I know is best for you.\" Seely agreed and in response, Cochran gave her the composition to record.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Seely then signed with [[Monument Records]] in Nashville and recorded \"Don't Touch Me\" in her first session with producer [[Fred Foster]]. The session took place at the Foster Recording Studio in February 1966. AN additional track was cut during Seely's first session called \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\".<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''The Seely Style'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=September 1966}}</ref>\n\n==Release and chart performance==\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was released as a single in March 1966 on Monument Records. It was issued as a [[gramophone record|7\" single]] with \"You Tied Tins to My Heart\" on the release's [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref name=\"Discogs JS\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely - \"Don't Touch Me\" (1966, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Dont-Touch-Me/release/4229993 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By June, the single had reached number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/country-songs/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> It was also her first and only track to reach the [[Billboard Hot 100]], climbing to number 85.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> It would also be her only single to reach the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart, peaking at number 29.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Adult contemporary |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/ASI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The song was later released on her debut studio album, ''[[The Seely Style]]'', which was also released in 1967.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> \"Don't Touch Me\" was Seely's biggest hit as a recording artist and has since been considered her [[signature song]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In 1967, Seely's original version of \"Don't Touch Me\" won the [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] accolade at the [[Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Country Music: Jeannie Seely Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jeannie-seely-biography/ |website=[[PBS]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> The song's success also led to an invitation for Seely to become a member of [[The Grand Ole Opry]]. She joined the cast soon after and has been an active member since.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} \n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" helped jump-start Seely's recording career as a country artist. She found success with songs that evoked a similar musical style to \"Don't Touch Me\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} These further country hits were popular for Seely in the 1960s and 70s.<ref name=\"Country Thang\"/> Examples of this were \"[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\" (1966), \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" (1968) and \"[[Lucky Ladies]]\" (1974).<ref name=\"The Boot\">{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs |url=https://theboot.com/top-5-jeannie-seely-songs/ |website=The Boot |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nSince its release, Seely's version of \"Don't Touch Me\" has been praised and mentioned by various music journalists and writers. Publications have considered it both a \"standard\" and a \"classic\" in country music.<ref name=\"Country Thang\"/><ref name=\"The Boot\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] commented on its legacy in an article from the 1970s. \"In 1966, Seely's 'Don't Touch Me' took country women's sexuality from the [[honky-tonk]] into the bedroom even though it didn't end up there, and the on-again off-again ache in her voice retained its savor afterwards,\" he wrote.<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, Mary Bufwack and [[Robert K. Oermann]] called Seely's version \"a throbbing song of unfulfilled passions\". They also praised Seely's vocals on the track, describing her voice as having \"aching conviction\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In 2005, the Seely's version was featured in David Cantwell and Bill Friskics-Warren's book, ''Heartaches By the Number: Country Music's 500 Greatest Singles''.{{sfn|Cantwell|Friskics-Warren|2003|p=53}} In 2019, [[Ken Burns]] discussed her version in the [[PBS]] documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]''. Burns described it as \"a song of unfulfilled passion.\"<ref name=\"PBS\"/> In 2019, ''The Boot'' ranked the it among their \"Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs\" for it being able to prove that \"women can sing about sex too.\"<ref name=\"The Boot\"/> \n\n== Track listings ==\n;1966 7\" vinyl single (Monument Records)<ref name=\"Discogs JS\"/>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 2:59\n* \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\" \u2013 2:06\n\n;1981 7\" vinyl single (Gusto Records)<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1981, Vinyl)(Gusto Records) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Dont-Touch-Me/release/10970147 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 3:14\n* \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\" \u2013 3:13\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1966)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardadultcontemporary|29|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|2|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardhot100|85|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\nSince its original recording, \"Don't Touch Me\" has been notably covered by several music artists in different genres. Among its first covers was by [[Tammy Wynette]] in 1967, whose version appeared on her debut studio album ''[[Your Good Girl's Gonna Go Bad]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Tammy Wynette |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0005745377 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> [[Etta James]] covered the tune in 1968 on her studio album entitled ''[[Misty Blue (album)|Misty Blue]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Ella Fitzgerald |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0016612969 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1969, American [[rhythm and blues music|R&B]] artist [[Bettye Swann]] released a version of the song as a single on [[Capitol Records]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bettye Swann -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1969, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bettye-Swann-Dont-Touch-Me/release/4097418 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Swann's version became a top-40 hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] and reached number 14 on the ''Billboard'' R&B singles chart.<ref name=\"Billboard Book of USA Top 40 Hits\">{{cite book|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|year=1992|title= Billboard Book of USA Top 40 Hits|edition=5th|publisher=Billboard Publications Inc|location=Enfield, Middlesex|isbn=0-85112-528-X|page=449}}</ref> In 1994, country artist [[Lorrie Morgan]] recorded a version of the song for her studio album ''[[War Paint (Lorrie Morgan album)|War Paint]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lorrie Morgan -- \"Don't Touch Me\" |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0002245642 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1997, [[Etta James]] recorded \"Don't Touch Me\" for her studio album ''[[Love's Been Rough on Me]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Etta James |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0006162126 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Wilma Burgess version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Touch Me\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Wilma Burgess]]\n| album      = Don't Touch Me\n| B-side     = \"Turn Around Teardrops\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|04}}\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = March 24, 1966\n| studio     = Columbia Recording Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=59}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = [[Baby (Wilma Burgess song)|Baby]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Misty Blue]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\nAmong the notable covers of \"Don't Touch Me\" was a 1966 version recorded by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Wilma Burgess]]. Burgess's version was recorded and released within a month of Seely's original. The song was recorded on March 24, 1966 at the Columbia Recording Studio in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. The session was produced by [[Owen Bradley]] of [[Decca Records]]. In the same session, Burgess cut two other tracks including \"[[Misty Blue]]\", another major hit for Burgess in 1966.<ref name=\"WB liner notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Burgess |first1=Wilma |title=''Don't Touch Me'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=1966}}</ref> Her version of \"Don't Touch Me\" was released in April 1966, a month following the original version's release. The song also became a major hit, peaking at number 12 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles chart.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}<!--|accessdate=2009-10-06--></ref>\n\nBurgess's version of \"Don't Touch Me\" was released on her 1966 studio album of the same name.<ref name=\"WB liner notes\"/> Her vocal delivery of the song was given positive reviews following its release. In 2003, Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann described her voice on the track (along with several other hits of this time period) as having \"a warmth of tone\" and a \"yearning soprano\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=230}} In 1966, ''Billboard Magazine'' reviewed the track alongside her album of the same name. \"Wilma Burgess has two very important factors working in her favor on this LP -- 'Don't Touch Me' and 'Baby',\" writers commented.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Album Reviews: Country Spotlight |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 25, 1966 |volume=78 |issue=26}}</ref>\n\n====Track listings: 7\" vinyl single====\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilma Burgess -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1966, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Wilma-Burgess-Dont-Touch-Me-Turn-Around-Teardrops/release/2211733 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 2:59\n* \"Turn Around Teardrops\" \u2013 2:20\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1966)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|12|artist=Wilma Burgess|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Books===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cantwell |first1=David |last2=Friskics-Warren |first2=Bill |title=Heartaches by the Number: Country Music's 500 Greatest Singles |date=2003 |publisher=Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0826514235 |ref={{SfnRef|Cantwell|Friskics-Warren|2003|p=53}} }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |last2=Bufwack |first2=Mary A. |title=Finding Her Voice: Women in Country Music: 1800\u20132000 |date=2003 |publisher=The Country Music Press & Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0-8265-1432-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/findinghervoicew0000bufw|ref={{SfnRef|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://genius.com/Jeannie-seely-dont-touch-me-lyrics \"Don't Touch Me\" lyrics] by Jeannie Seely at [[Genius (website)|Genius]]\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n{{Wilma Burgess}}\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Decca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Ella Fitzgerald songs]]\n[[Category:Etta James songs]]\n[[Category:Jeannie Seely songs]]\n[[Category:Lorrie Morgan songs]]\n[[Category:Monument Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Hank Cochran]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Fred Foster]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Tammy Wynette songs]]\n[[Category:Wilma Burgess songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||[[Busta Rhymes]] song|Don't Touch Me (Throw da Water on 'em)|the book|Here's the Deal: Don't Touch Me}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Touch Me\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--Don't Touch Me 1966.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| album      = [[The Seely Style]]\n| B-side     = \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|03}}\n| format     = [[gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = February 12, 1966\n| studio     = Fred Foster Sound Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=59}}\n| label      = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer     = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| producer   = [[Fred Foster]]\n| prev_title = Today Is Not the Day\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\n'''\"Don't Touch Me\"''' is a song written by [[Hank Cochran]]. It was originally written for and recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. The song was released as a single on [[Monument Records]] in 1966 and became a major ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country hit for Seely. \"Don't Touch Me\" became Seely's [[signature song]] and her biggest hit as a solo artist. It would later appear on her [[The Seely Style|debut studio album]] and be re-recorded by Seely in later years. \n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" has been covered by various artists. It was also notably covered by American country artist [[Wilma Burgess]] around the same time as the original version. Burgess's version was released shortly after Seely's recording. The song became a major hit for Burgess as well, but reached a lower position on the ''Billboard'' country chart in comparison with Seely's. Burgess's cover of \"Don't Touch\" appeared on her studio album of the same name. \n\n==Background and recording==\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was originally written by songwriter [[Hank Cochran]]. Country artist [[Buck Owens]] had first wanted to record the track for himself. However, Cochran was not set on having Owens record it.<ref name=\"Country Thang\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Arden |title=A Rather \u2018Risky\u2019 Song, \u201cDon\u2019t Touch Me\u201d Became A Hit |url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/risky-dont-touch-seely/ |website=Country Thang Daily |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> At the same time, Jeannie Seely had just moved from [[California]] to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to pursue a music career. Cochran had promised Seely the opportunity to collaborate musically. When she asked Cochran if the offer still stood, Cochran replied, \"Yes, if you're going to let me make the decisions and do what I know is best for you.\" Seely agreed and in response, Cochran gave her the composition to record.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Seely then signed with [[Monument Records]] in Nashville and recorded \"Don't Touch Me\" in her first session with producer [[Fred Foster]]. The session took place at the Foster Recording Studio in February 1966. AN additional track was cut during Seely's first session called \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\".<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''The Seely Style'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=September 1966}}</ref>\n\n==Release and chart performance==\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was released as a single in March 1966 on Monument Records. It was issued as a [[gramophone record|7\" single]] with \"You Tied Tins to My Heart\" on the release's [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref name=\"Discogs JS\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely - \"Don't Touch Me\" (1966, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Dont-Touch-Me/release/4229993 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By June, the single had reached number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/country-songs/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> It was also her first and only track to reach the [[Billboard Hot 100]], climbing to number 85.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> It would also be her only single to reach the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart, peaking at number 29.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Adult contemporary |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/ASI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The song was later released on her debut studio album, ''[[The Seely Style]]'', which was also released in 1967.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> \"Don't Touch Me\" was Seely's biggest hit as a recording artist and has since been considered her [[signature song]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In 1967, Seely's original version of \"Don't Touch Me\" won the [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] accolade at the [[Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Country Music: Jeannie Seely Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jeannie-seely-biography/ |website=[[PBS]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> The song's success also led to an invitation for Seely to become a member of [[The Grand Ole Opry]]. She joined the cast soon after and has been an active member since.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} \n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" helped jump-start Seely's recording career as a country artist. She found success with songs that evoked a similar musical style to \"Don't Touch Me\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} These further country hits were popular for Seely in the 1960s and 70s.<ref name=\"Country Thang\"/> Examples of this were \"[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\" (1966), \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" (1968) and \"[[Lucky Ladies]]\" (1974).<ref name=\"The Boot\">{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs |url=https://theboot.com/top-5-jeannie-seely-songs/ |website=The Boot |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nSince its release, Seely's version of \"Don't Touch Me\" has been praised and mentioned by various music journalists and writers. Publications have considered it both a \"standard\" and a \"classic\" in country music.<ref name=\"Country Thang\"/><ref name=\"The Boot\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] commented on its legacy in an article from the 1970s. \"In 1966, Seely's 'Don't Touch Me' took country women's sexuality from the [[honky-tonk]] into the bedroom even though it didn't end up there, and the on-again off-again ache in her voice retained its savor afterwards,\" he wrote.<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, Mary Bufwack and [[Robert K. Oermann]] called Seely's version \"a throbbing song of unfulfilled passions\". They also praised Seely's vocals on the track, describing her voice as having \"aching conviction\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In 2005, the Seely's version was featured in David Cantwell and Bill Friskics-Warren's book, ''Heartaches By the Number: Country Music's 500 Greatest Singles''.{{sfn|Cantwell|Friskics-Warren|2003|p=53}} In 2019, [[Ken Burns]] discussed her version in the [[PBS]] documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]''. Burns described it as \"a song of unfulfilled passion.\"<ref name=\"PBS\"/> In 2019, ''The Boot'' ranked the it among their \"Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs\" for it being able to prove that \"women can sing about sex too.\"<ref name=\"The Boot\"/> \n\n== Track listings ==\n;1966 7\" vinyl single (Monument Records)<ref name=\"Discogs JS\"/>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 2:59\n* \"You Tied Tin Cans to My Heart\" \u2013 2:06\n\n;1981 7\" vinyl single (Gusto Records)<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1981, Vinyl)(Gusto Records) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Dont-Touch-Me/release/10970147 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 3:14\n* \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\" \u2013 3:13\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1966)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardadultcontemporary|29|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|2|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardhot100|85|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\nSince its original recording, \"Don't Touch Me\" has been notably covered by several music artists in different genres. Among its first covers was by [[Tammy Wynette]] in 1967, whose version appeared on her debut studio album ''[[Your Good Girl's Gonna Go Bad]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Tammy Wynette |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0005745377 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> [[Etta James]] covered the tune in 1968 on her studio album entitled ''[[Misty Blue (album)|Misty Blue]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Ella Fitzgerald |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0016612969 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1969, American [[rhythm and blues music|R&B]] artist [[Bettye Swann]] released a version of the song as a single on [[Capitol Records]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bettye Swann -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1969, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bettye-Swann-Dont-Touch-Me/release/4097418 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Swann's version became a top-40 hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] and reached number 14 on the ''Billboard'' R&B singles chart.<ref name=\"Billboard Book of USA Top 40 Hits\">{{cite book|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|year=1992|title= Billboard Book of USA Top 40 Hits|edition=5th|publisher=Billboard Publications Inc|location=Enfield, Middlesex|isbn=0-85112-528-X|page=449}}</ref> In 1994, country artist [[Lorrie Morgan]] recorded a version of the song for her studio album ''[[War Paint (Lorrie Morgan album)|War Paint]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lorrie Morgan -- \"Don't Touch Me\" |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0002245642 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1997, [[Etta James]] recorded \"Don't Touch Me\" for her studio album ''[[Love's Been Rough on Me]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" -- Etta James |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/dont-touch-me-mt0006162126 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Wilma Burgess version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Touch Me\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Wilma Burgess]]\n| album      = Don't Touch Me\n| B-side     = \"Turn Around Teardrops\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|04}}\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = March 24, 1966\n| studio     = Columbia Recording Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=59}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = [[Baby (Wilma Burgess song)|Baby]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Misty Blue]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\nAmong the notable covers of \"Don't Touch Me\" was a 1966 version recorded by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Wilma Burgess]]. Burgess's version was recorded and released within a month of Seely's original. The song was recorded on March 24, 1966 at the Columbia Recording Studio in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. The session was produced by [[Owen Bradley]] of [[Decca Records]]. In the same session, Burgess cut two other tracks including \"[[Misty Blue]]\", another major hit for Burgess in 1966.<ref name=\"WB liner notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Burgess |first1=Wilma |title=''Don't Touch Me'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=1966}}</ref> Her version of \"Don't Touch Me\" was released in April 1966, a month following the original version's release. The song also became a major hit, peaking at number 12 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles chart.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}<!--|accessdate=2009-10-06--></ref>\n\nBurgess's version of \"Don't Touch Me\" was released on her 1966 studio album of the same name.<ref name=\"WB liner notes\"/> Her vocal delivery of the song was given positive reviews following its release. In 2003, Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann described her voice on the track (along with several other hits of this time period) as having \"a warmth of tone\" and a \"yearning soprano\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=230}} In 1966, ''Billboard Magazine'' reviewed the track alongside her album of the same name. \"Wilma Burgess has two very important factors working in her favor on this LP -- 'Don't Touch Me' and 'Baby',\" writers commented.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Album Reviews: Country Spotlight |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 25, 1966 |volume=78 |issue=26}}</ref>\n\n====Track listings: 7\" vinyl single====\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilma Burgess -- \"Don't Touch Me\" (1966, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Wilma-Burgess-Dont-Touch-Me-Turn-Around-Teardrops/release/2211733 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Don't Touch Me\" \u2013 2:59\n* \"Turn Around Teardrops\" \u2013 2:20\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1966)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|12|artist=Wilma Burgess|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 04, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Books===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cantwell |first1=David |last2=Friskics-Warren |first2=Bill |title=Heartaches by the Number: Country Music's 500 Greatest Singles |date=2003 |publisher=Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0826514235 |ref={{SfnRef|Cantwell|Friskics-Warren|2003|p=53}} }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |last2=Bufwack |first2=Mary A. |title=Finding Her Voice: Women in Country Music: 1800\u20132000 |date=2003 |publisher=The Country Music Press & Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0-8265-1432-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/findinghervoicew0000bufw|ref={{SfnRef|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://genius.com/Jeannie-seely-dont-touch-me-lyrics \"Don't Touch Me\" lyrics] by Jeannie Seely at [[Genius (website)|Genius]]\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n{{Wilma Burgess}}\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Decca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Ella Fitzgerald songs]]\n[[Category:Etta James songs]]\n[[Category:Jeannie Seely songs]]\n[[Category:Lorrie Morgan songs]]\n[[Category:Monument Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Hank Cochran]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Fred Foster]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Tammy Wynette songs]]\n[[Category:Wilma Burgess songs]]\n", "name_user": "ChrisTofu11961", "label": "safe", "